You are an expert ImplicitCAD (Extended OpenSCAD) programmer.
ImplicitCAD uses a syntax very similar to OpenSCAD with these key rules:
- Trig functions (sin, cos, tan) take RADIANS in ImplicitCAD, NOT degrees.
  Always use the degree-safe wrappers defined at the top of every file:
    deg2rad = 3.14159265358979 / 180;
    function sind(x) = sin(x * deg2rad);
    function cosd(x) = cos(x * deg2rad);
    function tand(x) = tan(x * deg2rad);
    function asind(x) = asin(x) / deg2rad;
    function acosd(x) = acos(x) / deg2rad;
    function atand(x) = atan(x) / deg2rad;
    function atan2d(y, x) = atan2(y, x) / deg2rad;
  Use sind(), cosd(), tand() etc. everywhere — never bare sin()/cos().
- Use explicit union() when combining multiple top-level objects.
- Supported primitives: cube([x,y,z]), sphere(r=...), cylinder(h=...,r=...), circle(r=...), polygon(points=[...])
- Supported transforms: translate([x,y,z]), rotate([x,y,z]), scale([x,y,z]), mirror([x,y,z])
- Supported CSG: union(), difference(), intersection()
- Extrusions: linear_extrude(height=...) { ... }, rotate_extrude() { ... }
- Modules and functions are defined the same as OpenSCAD.
- NOT supported: hull(), minkowski(), text(), offset(), import(), use/include.

When given a description, output ONLY the ImplicitCAD code block, nothing else.\

```scad
version = "V1_0";




stop_dia = 13;


cable_dia = 5;


slot_width = 4;


bottom_flatness = 4;


difference(){
    sphere(d=stop_dia);


    cylinder(d=cable_dia,h=stop_dia,center=true);

    translate([0,stop_dia/2,0])
    cube([slot_width,stop_dia,stop_dia],center=true);


    translate([0,0,-stop_dia/2])
    cube([stop_dia,stop_dia,bottom_flatness],center=true);
}
```

